            <div class="assessment-body ">
                <h2 class="inrule">
                    Chasms & Stages: Major Milestones on the Decision Automation Journey
                </h2>
                    <p>
                    One of the greatest challenges in progressing from stage to stage on the decision automation journey is maintaining the foundational programs that support each evolution. For example, providing a centralized location for business logic can reduce the overhead of maintenance that was required in Stages 0-2, while providing a wide range of benefits to application development and deployment overall.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                    Say your organization is past the Data Capability Chasm, enjoying some of the advantages of Stage 4 and 5, but there’s a gap in the maintenance of business logic in a centralized location. Perhaps you’ve got a rogue application using a set of business rules that is different than (and out of sync with) the rest of the applications in your enterprise stack. You are likely losing out on the contribution of those benefits initially gained at Stage 3 or 4.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                    Bottom line, the cumulative impact of the capabilities developed at each stage has a deep influence on how effective the later stages can be, increasing the leap required to overcome both the Automation Chasm and the Data Capability Chasm.
                    </p>
            </div>
            <div class="assessment-body ">
                <h2 class="inrule">
                    The Automation Chasm
                </h2>
                    <p>
                    The Automation Chasm is the first major hurdle to decision automation. This chasm represents the evolution from manual decision making (human reviewing) to automated decision making. For some, a shift is first made by adopting off-the-shelf software with built-in logic, often in the form of a settings page or a configuration during initial set up. And in many cases, companies find themselves facing the Automation Chasm when these software solutions begin to limit how businesses can operate or how they deliver superior digital customer experiences.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                    This limitation usually leads to a custom software development initiative as an attempt to cross the chasm. In support of the initiative, key business logic is defined in software requirements documentation. However, once this bridge is crossed, there exists a scattered repository of business logic that may be inconsistently applied across multiple custom or semi-custom software solutions.
                    </p>
                    <p>   
                    Regardless, approaching the Automation Chasm with a clear set of well-documented business logic ensures the crossing will be faster and smoother than without, and will prepare your business for future stages of evolution. 
                    </p>
            </div>
            <div class="assessment-body footer">
                <h2 class="inrule">
                    The Data Capability Chasm
                </h2>
                    <p>
                        The second major hurdle, the Data Capability Chasm, is about shrinking the time between rule execution and gathering the insights needed to improve operations. This hurdle requires capabilities to be developed both within an organization’s employee base, as well as within its enterprise technology stack.    
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Dynamic pricing rules are a particularly effective example where the time between rule execution and insight can make a difference, where demand can be tracked to take advantage of what the market is willing to transact that day, hour, or minute.  
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        Using that example, consider similar opportunities in your operations where using feedback from real-time rule executions, or data transactions, can impact a decision. Shining a spotlight on these areas can show where you may want to invest in. For example, 1) building the internal business analysis capability and 2) automating changes to business rules in response to the latest business rule executions. 
                    </p>
                    <p>  
                        These initiatives are often more easily identified than completed and may take more time to implement than previous evolutionary steps on the journey.
                    </p>   
            </div>
